<TITLE> UK tycoon denies breaking Zimbabwe exchange rules </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 HARARE, Jan 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British property tycoon Nicholas van Hoogstraten denied on Monday that he had violated Zimbabwe's foreign currency exchange rules. The 63-year-old, who was arrested last Thursday in a night-time police raid on his home, has been charged with levying rentals on his properties in foreign currency contrary to Zimbabwean law. Van Hoogstraten, who had been due to appear in court on Monday, had not done so by close of business and his lawyers said he was applying to the High Court to be brought to court. "They don't appear eager to bring him to court, so we'll be making an application to the High Court shortly to have him brought here," said George Chikumbirike, who is leading Van Hoogstraten's defence team. Earlier, Van Hoogstraten issued a statement denying any wrongdoing and also said he had not fallen out with President Robert Mugabe's government over his arrest. "The charges are a deliberate and malicious entrapment scheme. I deny all of them," van Hoogstraten said. bdnews24.com/lq/2159hrs Van Hoogstraten is being charged under Exchange Control regulations and will also face charges linked to pornographic material found in his house. The real estate developer owns about 200 residential and business properties in Zimbabwe. "There is nothing political about my arrest," van Hoogstraten said in a statement." "I would like to stress that the misconception which might arise in the press or elsewhere that I have fallen out with the Zimbabwean aut
